The data are from a survey related to learning statistics from a statistics course organized in 2014. It includes data from 166 participants (rows). Columns have responder demographic information (age and gender), exam points (points), and attitude towards learning statistics. The central measure is learning method measured by three dimensions (deep, surface and strategic).

3. and 4. Linear regression

model1 <- learning2023 %>% 
  lm(points ~ gender+age+attitude, data =.)

summary(model1)

The P-value of the model is 5.5x10-8. Based on the multiple R-squared value, the model explains 20% of the variation in the exam scores. There is statistically significant correlation between attitude and exam points (P=8.3x10-9). It seems that better attitude towards statistics yields higher points in the exam. Gender or age were not statistically significant predictors of exam points, thus we remove them from the model.

model2 <- learning2023 %>% 
  lm(points ~ attitude, data =.)

summary(model2)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude, data = .)

## F-statistic: 38.61 on 1 and 164 DF,  p-value: 4.119e-09

When age and gender were removed from the model, attitude remained as significant variable. The P-value of the model is now a little bit smaller (P=4.1-9). Based on this model, attitude correlates with exam results. The estimate trend is positive, which means that attitude has positive correlation with exam points. Multiple R-squared of the model is 0.19, which means that attitude explains 19% of the variation in exam scores in this dataset.

5. Plotting the linear regression

library("ggfortify")
autoplot(model2)

Residuals vs fitted values plot tells whether the residuals vary depending on the fitted value. Based on the plot it seems that fitted values donât affect the residuals. Mean (blue line) seems to be a horizontal line.

In the QQ-plot there are few outliers in the extreme ends. However, in the middle part it seems to correlate quite well.

In the residuals vs leverage plot, observations seem to be within the Cookâs distance.

In conclusion, based on the model it seems that motivation towards statistics has positive correlation with exam points. The residual plots and normal QQ-plot seem to be ok. There are few outlier, which can be seen especially in the QQ-plot but otherwise it looks okay. At least it seems that there is not any systematic problem with the data. There are few outlier in the dataset, but it does not have big impact on the results.

The dataset includes data from two Portuguese schools. It includes data for 370 students (rows) and 35 different attributes (columns). It has data for two student demographics such as sex, age and home address type (urban or rural). For student performance it includes data from Math and Portuguese classes from three grades.

##Exploring student alcohol consumption

3. setting the study hypothesis

I decided to study how sex, address, paid, and absences may affect alcohol use. My hypothesis is that males use more alcohol than females. address variable tells if the studentâs home address is rural (R) or urban (U), and I think that there may be differences between urban and rural locations. paid variable tell if student paid for extra classes in either of the subjects (math or portugal). My hypothesis is that those who paid for extra classes drink less alcohol. absences is the number of studentâs school absences. My hypothesis is that those who drink more alcohol have more absences.

#creating dataset with only the selected variables
model_data <- student_data %>%

## 5 absences       1.10     0.0235      4.18 0.0000296     1.06       1.16

In the table above, estimate column tells the odd ratios, while conf.low is the lower limit and conf.high the upper limit of 95% confidence interval.

In the logistic regression model sex and absences had statistically significant association.

Hypothesis regarding sex was that high use of alcohol is more common among males. The logistic regression model supports this hypothesis and the odd ratio for high alcohol use is 2.95.

Another hypothesis was that there is difference between rural and urban areas. The difference is not statistically significant, but the p-value is quite small (0.08), and there seems to be at least trend that alcohol use is less common in urban areas (odd ratio: 0.62, 95% confidence interval: 0.36-1.07).

Hypothesis for association between paid classes and alcohol use does not seem to be correct. There was no difference according to this analysis.

As per hypothesis, absences correlated with high alcohol use. P-value was small (2.9x10-9). For the absences the odd ratio was 1.1 and 95% confidence interval 1.06-1.16).

fit2 <- glm(high_use~sex+absences, family = binomial, data =model_data) #new model with only statistically significant variables

summary(fit2)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = high_use ~ sex + absences, family = binomial, data = model_data)
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)

## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 452.04  on 369  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 415.66  on 367  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 421.66
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 4
probabilities <- predict.glm(fit2, type = "response") #predict probabilites based on the glm-model

model_data <- model_data %>% 
    mutate(probability = probabilities,
           prediction = probability>0.5) #create prediction variable, which is TRUE when probability > 0.5

prediction_table <- table(high_use = model_data$high_use, prediction = model_data$prediction)
prediction_table

7. cross-validation

loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}


# K-fold cross-validation
cv <- cv.glm(data = model_data, cost = loss_func, glmfit = fit2, K = nrow(model_data))

# average number of wrong predictions in the cross validation
cv$delta[1]

##Exploring student alcohol consumption

3. setting the study hypothesis

I decided to study how sex, address, paid, and absences may affect alcohol use. My hypothesis is that males use more alcohol than females. address variable tells if the studentâs home address is rural (R) or urban (U), and I think that there may be differences between urban and rural locations. paid variable tell if student paid for extra classes in either of the subjects (math or portugal). My hypothesis is that those who paid for extra classes drink less alcohol. absences is the number of studentâs school absences. My hypothesis is that those who drink more alcohol have more absences.

In the table above, estimate column tells the odd ratios, while conf.low is the lower limit and conf.high the upper limit of 95% confidence interval.

In the logistic regression model sex and absences had statistically significant association.

Hypothesis regarding sex was that high use of alcohol is more common among males. The logistic regression model supports this hypothesis and the odd ratio for high alcohol use is 2.95.

Another hypothesis was that there is difference between rural and urban areas. The difference is not statistically significant, but the p-value is quite small (0.08), and there seems to be at least trend that alcohol use is less common in urban areas (odd ratio: 0.62, 95% confidence interval: 0.36-1.07).

Hypothesis for association between paid classes and alcohol use does not seem to be correct. There was no difference according to this analysis.

As per hypothesis, absences correlated with high alcohol use. P-value was small (2.9x10-9). For the absences the odd ratio was 1.1 and 95% confidence interval 1.06-1.16).

Create categorical crime variable

boston_scaled <- data.frame(boston_scaled) # convert to data frame
bins <- quantile(boston_scaled$crim)

# create a categorical variable 'crime'
crime <- cut(boston_scaled$crim, breaks = bins, include.lowest = TRUE, labels = c("low", "med_low", "med_high", "high"))


# remove original crim from the dataset
boston_scaled_ <- dplyr::select(boston_scaled, -crim)

# add the new categorical value to scaled data
boston_scaled <- data.frame(boston_scaled, crime)

# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  graphics::arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

# plot the lda results (select both lines and execute them at the same time!)
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2,col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 2)
